===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|castle|lang=enm}}, {{term|castel|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|castel|lang=ang}}, {{term|castell|lang=ang}}, {{term|cæstel|lang=ang}}, {{m|ang|ċeastel||a town, village, castle}}, borrowed from {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{term|castellum||small camp, fort|lang=la}}, diminutive of {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|castrum||camp, fort, citadel, stronghold|lang=la}}, possibly from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*kat-||hut, shed}}. Parallel borrowings (from Late Latin or Old French) are {{etyl|sco|-}} {{term|castel|lang=sco}}, {{term|castell||castle|lang=sco}}, {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|kastiel||castle|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|kasteel||castle|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Kastell||castle|lang=de}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|kastel||citadel|lang=da}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|kastell||citadel|lang=sv}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|kastali||castle|lang=is}}. The Middle English word was reinforced by {{etyl|xno|en}}/{{etyl|ONF.|-}} {{term|castel|lang=fro}}, itself from {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{term|castellum||small camp, fort|lang=la}} (compare modern French {{term|château|lang=fr}} from Old French {{term|chastel|lang=fro}}). If {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|castrum||camp, fort, citadel, stronghold|lang=la}} is from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*kat-||hut, shed}}, {{etyl|la|-}} {{term|casa||cottage, hut|lang=la}} is related. Possibly related also to {{etyl|got|-}} {{term|||tr=hēþjō|chamber|lang=got}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|heaþor||restraint, confinement, enclosure, prison|lang=ang}}. See also {{l/en|casino}}, {{l/en|cassock}}.

