===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A large [[building]] that is [[fortified]] and contains many [[defence]]s; in previous ages often inhabited by a [[nobleman]] or [[king]].
# {{context|chess|lang=en}} An instance of [[castling]].
# {{context|chess|informal|lang=en}} A [[rook]]; a [[chess]] piece shaped like a castle [[tower]].
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} A [[close helmet]].
#* '''1786''', Francis Grose, ''A Treatise on Ancient Armour and Weapons'', p. 12,
#*: The '''castle''' was perhaps a figurative name for a close headpiece deduced from its enclosing and defending the head, as a castle did the whole body; or a corruption from the Old French word ''[[casquetel]]'', a small or light helmet.
# {{context|dated|lang=en}} Any strong, imposing, and stately mansion.
# {{context|dated|lang=en}} A small tower, as on a ship, or an elephant's back.

====Usage notes====
For the chess piece, chess players prefer the term [[rook]].

